    "analysis": "Previous step computed global statistics (count, mean, min, P5, P95, max) for the top-30 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series ranked by spread (P95-P5). Key observations: these top-varying series are dominated by JVM/process CPU and node disk/inode metrics and they have full coverage (30 points) across the incident window. Error logs show repeated 'failed to retrieve ads' warnings on frontend pods near 22:59, so frontend-related issues are a lead. According to the workflow, next we must perform anomaly detection across resource-related metrics using global thresholds (P95/P5 computed across the full series) then inspect which series show anomalies inside the incident window. To stay output-bounded and focus on likely root-cause dimensions, we should scan metrics whose KPI names look resource-related (cpu, memory, disk, io, fs, HeapMemoryUsage, ProcessCpuTime, container_spec, network, packet, retrans, latency, read, write). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series we'll compute global P95 and P5 (full series), then count how many points in the incident window exceed P95 (high anomalies) or fall below P5 (low anomalies), and record earliest anomaly timestamps. Ranking by total in-window anomalies will narrow candidate faulty components for subsequent fault identification and trace/log correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Scan metric.csv for KPI names containing any of these substrings (case-insensitive): 'cpu','memory','disk','io','fs','HeapMemoryUsage','ProcessCpuTime','container_spec','network','packet','retrans','latency','read','write'. For each matching (cmdb_id,kpi_name):\n1) Compute global P95 and P5 using the full available points for that series (do NOT filter by the incident window when computing P95/P5).\n2) For the incident window 2022-03-21 22:30:00 to 2022-03-21 22:59:59 (UTC+8), compute: points_in_window, number of points > P95 (high_anomalies_count) and earliest timestamp of such high anomaly (or null), number of points < P5 (low_anomalies_count) and earliest timestamp of such low anomaly (or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window.\nReturn the top 20 series ranked by (high_anomalies_count + low_anomalies_count) descending. For each returned row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count (full-series count), P5, P95, points_in_window, high_anomalies_count, earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomalies_count, earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Return as JSON-serializable table and limit rows to 20."
